    Manymoon is a net-based image sharing forum built around anonymity and barebone moderation, making it an "anything goes" sort of community.  Due to its structure, it has gained a reputation for being ruled by "trolls" and "schemers", types of person with a reputation for causing distress and disarray for entertainment or other gains.  Because of this, many terrible misdeeds done across the [!2 Silver Stream] have been linked to groups of anonymous people coming together on Manymoon with a common goal in mind.  This is a double-edged blade, however; many a time these groups of people have come together to do something understood to be illegal, but also widely agreed to be nonetheless ethical and benevolent. Often seen by many as a "total wildcard group", people have mixed opinions on Manymoon and it's netizens.  Notable deeds done on the forum are numerous, such as their many terrorist hunts on the /th/ thread, and many, many "Pranks" pulled on prominent citizens, usually causing disarray.  Manymoon is a [!3 Tunnel Site], meaning that the location of its servers are unknown.  Manymoon is run by a head admin and owner known as HolyTay.  Most Manymoon users just refer to him as "Tay".�css
    Manymoon is divided into multiple sections called "threads".  The topic of a thread dictates what is discussed and shared there.  The proper way to write a thread's name is to terminate both ends with a forward slash (/) -- for example, a thread called "internet" would be shortened to "net" written "/net/".  Some notable threads are:
        /main/, for anything -- this thread has no topic restrictions;
        /build/, for discussing architecture and DIY projects;
        /videos/, for discussing and sharing full-motion videos;
        /fiction/, for sharing and discussing fictional material;
        /pranks/, for planning, executing, and sharing pranks at any scale;
        /power/, for discussing energy production, use, and sources;
        /pics/, for sharing interesting photots;
        /sky/, for discusing space infrastructure, trade, and travel;
        /bs/, (standing for "Big State"), for discussing the broader [!4 GCP] confederal government;
        /pop/, for discussing popular culture;
        /qi/, for discussing [!5 magic and qi invocation];
        /d/, which was originally for debate, but is now more oriented around politics in general;
        /dc/, for discussing Defence Contracting, mercenary work and the [!6 Order of Paladins];
        /rel/, for discussing [!7 religions] and religious practices;
        /news/, for discussing current events and news;
        /trade/, for arranging deals and exhanges between users;
        /hdrugs/, standing for "hard drugs", for discussing use and production of illegal substances.  Though selling on the thread is prohibited;
        /drugs/, like /hdrugs/, but only permits posts about mostly-legal substances.
        /cash/, for discussing finances, investments, and stock trading;
        /cop/, for discussing crime, and sometimes teaming together to solve cases abroad;
        /th/, for discussing terrorism, mostly towards preventing acts of terror;�css
        /net/, for discussing [!8 websites] and [!9 internet culture];
        /chef/, for discussing food and the culinary arts;
        /funny/, for posting memes, jokes, and other funny content;
        /schitt/, which is like /funny/, but mainly revolves around feces as a punchline.  It has a poor reputation;
        /sport/, for discussing competitive games;
        /code/, for programming, trouble shooting, and discussion about general-purpose computers;
        /art/, for discussing, sharing, and drafting visual art;
        /mm/, for posts about the site itself and requesting creation or archival of threads;
        /c/, for discussing vehicles;
        /rp/, for finding partners for tabletop or free-form roleplay;
        /tay/, HolyTay's, the site owner, thread for blogging and personal use;
        /cl/, for creating cyphers and constructed languages;
        /bio/, for discussing biology, medicine, geneology, and genetic engineering;
        /vivo/, like /bio/, but specifically for discussing differences between lifeforms of different [!10 vivotypes];
        /tunes/, for discussing, sharing, and making music and sound;
        /lewd/, for discussing general erotica.  More specific erotica threads are /toys/, /cute/, /erp/, /cogniz/, /hot/, /sleek/, /dom/, /skin/, /fluff/, /toons/, and other threads with explicit names.
        State-oriented threads like /ar/, /bt/, /eq/, /ga/, /gm/, /it/, /lf/, /su/, /ty/, and /ur/ for discussing [!11 Armalai], [!12 Bius Tu], [!13 Deoria], [!14 Gallea], [!15 Ghillymede], [!16 Itascus], [!17 La`Foy], [!18 Solar Union], [!19 New Tyventia], and [!20 Neo Urra] respectively;
        And countless threads for minor subcultures and interests, from both on or off of the internet.�css
    There are hundreds of threads on Manymoon, each of which being further divided into "Topics" that discuss a specific instance of something, like a specific person, event, building, item, or location.  Manymoon is most popular among [!21 Unil]-speaking users, but, being an interstellar service, contains posts in hundreds of different languages.  For this, users can filter and sort threads by language.
    Every thread has its own rules and moderation team.  Admins of threads are assigned by HolyTay, Manymoon`s owner, himself, and admins of threads can assign moderators under them.  These admins and moderators typically choose to keep themselves entirely anonymous.

    While Manymoon`s minimal moderation and general "lawlessness" is paraded by its users, who are sometimes called "Moonies", outsiders view it as problematic.  While total anonymity and minimal restrictions is thought to be the pinacle of expressing one`s Free Speech, that doesn`t mean its without its problems; Manymoon, and some of its users, has been critisized for allowing commonly toxic, regressive, and hurtful ideas to propogate.  For some examples:
        multiple hatecrimes across the galaxy have been directly linked to discussions on /rel/, /bio/, and /d/;
        intentional misinformation campaigns have been directed on /news/, /d/, and /pranks/;
        distribution of variably-legal pornography on /lewd/ and /cogniz/;
        /schitt/ is notorious for discussing various, unpopular feces-related pranks in the real world, such as the "pooball incident" at a college-level [!22 Spoofball] tourney on [!16 Itascus];
        normalizing and advocating for dangerous or harmful sexualities on /toys/, /cogniz/, /toons/, and /cute/;
        /pranks/ and /schitt/ defecating on the driveway or vehicle of notorious politicians on multiple occasions;
        and objectification of marginal groups on /fluff/, /skin/, and /sleek/;�css
    As stated previously, however, while this anonymity enables people to gather and carry out acts of malice and chaos, it also enables them to carry out acts generally considered to be ethical and justified (even if illegal).  Some examples of these include:
        /qi/ has made many discoveries regarding [!23 Qi Energy] that incrementally advanced the art of spellcraft;
        users on /bio/ have managed to solve archeological mysteries across the galaxy;
        /th/ actively hunts down terrorist organizations by examining images, video, and reports available on the internet, as well as directing users in areas effected by terror groups to act as investigators and procure important information.  When the group gathers impactful intel, its shared on the thread and with local athourities;
        /cop/ has helped solve countless crimes by examining public evidence and crowdsourcing the tracking and identification of suspects, similar to /th/;
        some users on /news/ make it their duty to fact check politicians and talking heads in an effort to fight misinformation;
        /code/ and /sky/ worked together to organize tens of thousands of Moonies to connect their personal computers to work in tandem and act as one decentralized supercomputer.  This supercomputer was used to run simulated experiments, the results of which were used to increase the efficiency of space ship components.�css
    Manymoon started as a domestic [!24 Eriian] website at the address [!1 ER.MANYMOON] by a user who goes by "HolyTay" (commonly refered to as just "Tay").  According to Tay, Manymoon was created as a response to being banned from an unnamed social media in the year 81 for "unpopular opinions".  Manymoon`s servers were originally hosted on Erii, in HolyTay`s own home.  In 83, as Manymoon surpassed 5,500 daily active users and Tay`s home hardware was becomming stressed by the activity, he made a choice to start accepting paid ads in order to maintain more powerful hardware.  The Manymoon community was originally outraged by this news, but quickly accepted it as they noted the greatly improved performance of the previously-unreliable site.  From there, Manymoon`s popularity exploded, and Tay found himself with an enormous amount of income.
    At the same time, Manymoon began drawing ire from news outlets and authorities alike due to the criminal activity being openly discussed and even planned on the site.  Tay was given a Court Order from an [!24 Eriian] high court stating that Manymoon should be moderated to remove all illegal content, as well as limit hate speech.  Tay reluctantly agreed, but openly detested the decision on the /tay/ thread, arguing that it was a blow to the rights (specifically of Free Speech) of people on the site, to which many Moonies agreed.  
    Shortly after censorship began, Tay bought 117 [!25 quantum nodes], each with one end connected to the Manymoon servers; the other ends of these nodes were distributed across all populated worlds in the GCP.  Tay claimed that this was to improve connectivity to Manymoon, so that users could connect to the site through a proxy no matter where they were, instead of users having to connect to Manymoon through their ISP.  Many ISPs at the time charged a premium for galactic internet access, meaning that people that didn`t live on Erii might have to pay extra in order to access Manymoon.�css
    After Manymoon installed Quantum Nodes everywhere, the site experienced another explosion in popularity, as then anyone in [!2 Silver Stream] could access Manymoon at no added cost.  This also caused the volume of ad purchases on the site to skyrocket, leading to greater profits for the site.   However, it would soon be revealed that this enhanced availability was not the purpose of the quantum nodes.  On the 31st of Siltcrest, 84 P.W., Manymoon unexpectedly went down.  Attempting to access the website would just show a page with the following message:
        "Manymoon is down, but not for long.
        Starting today, our tongues are untied; we will no longer be censoring our users.
        Individual threads will still have their own rules, but we will not be bound by laws and court orders intended to silence diverse thought.
        No longer will Erii, nor any government, control our minds and dictate our words.

        Stay tuned."

    Seeing that the intentions stated in the message were in direct contradiction to HolyTay`s court order, authorities were quickly alerted, and officers were dispatched to check on him.  However, when they arrived at his residence, he was nowhere to be found, and Manymoon`s server hardware was gone.  His neighbors were questioned, and they described an unmarked van arriving at the residence the day prior.  They claim to have seen Tay and two unidentified [!26 Tuines] loading computer racks into the van, with Tay himself entering the van before all three drove off.  All attempts to track HolyTay down resulted in dead ends, and it is suspected that Tay had left the planet entirely.�css
    The next day, Manymoon went back online, only being able to be connected to through one of the 117 quantum nodes.  Now that the location of Tay and the Manymoon servers were completely unknown, Manymoon was effectively above litigation.  Many jurisdictions tried to block the site`s address on their worlds, but this wasn`t effective enough due to the number of redundant quantum nodes and proxies.  As the site entered a legal limbo, many advertizers pulled their ads from Manymoon.  Some advertizers did stay, however, maintaining income for the site.
    Today, Manymoon is more popular than ever, and the whereabouts of HolyTay are still unknown.  When discussing his living situation on the /tay/ thread, HolyTay claims he lives in "a 50-room underground mansion with a pool" -- this has been confirmed by pictures he shares to his thread.
